1.3 Exponential Waiting Times

The time until the next event, 
T, is exponentially distributed:
P(T>t)=e^âˆ’Î»t

Expected waiting time:
E[T]=1/Î»
	â€‹
This exponential distribution is memoryless, meaning the process â€œforgetsâ€ how long itâ€™s been since the last event. This property is unique to the exponential distribution, which is why Poisson processes are widely used in modelling markets.

2. Why This Matters in Quant Finance

Poisson processes appear in:

Limit order arrivals

Market orders hitting the book

Jump-diffusion models

Credit defaults / counterparty risk

Order flow imbalance models

Operational risk event modelling

High-frequency market microstructure

Even when real markets are more complicated, Poisson/exponential models form the backbone of many first-approximation models.

